<TITLE> PM claims 'clean slate' on corruption </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 23 (bdnews24.com)Prime minister Sheikh Hasina has dismissed talk of corruption in her government, claiming a clean slate during her government's first year office. "None could lodge a complaint of corruption against any minister by this time," she said, terming it the 'maximum success' story. Adding that her government had taken a strict stand against corruption, Hasina said, "We'll continue the anti-corruption drives. Corruption bars the development of a country's economy." Her statements came in the wake of allegations by a newspaper labelled pro-BNP that has accused Hasina's son Sajib Wazed Joy and the prime minister's energy adviser Toufique-e-Elahi Chowdury of taking bribes from a US oil company in return for lucrative energy deals in Bangladesh. 'STRONGER DEFENCE' Hasina was addressing the 11th graduation ceremony of the National Defence College at Mirpur Cantonment. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina on Wednesday said the country's armed forces will be further strengthened, while maintaining good relations with neighbouring countries. She also urged the armed forces to remain alert against any threat to the country's security, in a speech at the 11th graduation ceremony of the National Defence College at Mirpur Cantonment. "I hope you'll always be engaged in collecting and analysing information," the prime minister stressed. Hasina described the efforts by Sheikh Mujibur Rahman to build a modern and up to date armed forces. The prime minister said, "Bangladesh has succeeded combating terrorism while the blame of militancy is also washed away. "Terrorism and militancy, which violate the human rights and hit the humanity, are bar to the development of many countries. These days, it's not possible to keep eyes closed when the sovereignty of a country is under threat." Hasina said, "No country can run alone these days. The situation now is that everyone has to move with cooperation of the others. "We've to work together to fight poverty," she urged. "The government is sincerely working for the socio-economic development of the country." Hasina also said, trial of war criminals "will be launched immediately" while those involved in BDR mutiny and killing will also be tried. Regarding the Copenhagen Climate Conference, she said, "In the conference I highlighted the situation of vulnerable countries, and also called for raising an international fund for the affected countries to fight the situation." bdnews
